Emily Schmidt and Genta Mehmeti

2023-04-06

1 Understanding Quality Perceptions of Smartphones

The product management team intends to develop a deeper understanding of customers’ product quality perceptions regarding its constituent dimensions. The project team pursues the user-based perspective on product quality and accordingly characterizes perceived product quality as the customer’s judgment of the overall excellence, esteem, or superiority of a product (with respect to its intended purposes) relative to the alternative products. Researchers recognize that perceived product quality needs to be conceptualized as a multidimensional construct. Therefore, the team hopes to establish relevant quality dimensions that significantly define key outcome variables such as willingness to pay premium (WTPP) and repurchase intentions (RI). The operations management department hopes that this project will provide them with a criterion variable to assess the success or failure of their quality improvement initiatives.
- Resource: Case Study II

For Problem 1, certain quality variables were kept within the dataset for factor analysis per the case study’s directions. Out of the 33 variables, six have missing values (\(qd22\), \(qd26\), \(qd28\), \(qd29\), \(qd31\), and \(qd33\)). There are 270 NAs which accounts for 4.43% of the 1,014 smartphone customers. Therefore, the analysis will continue only using 969 observations.

All variables are integers and have a range of different values for the mean, median, minimum, maximum, and standard deviation. It is noticed that two of the 33 questions have a maximum of seven which indicates that those use another measurement scale. Additionally, for question \(qd13\), the minimum value is 2 while all other predictors have a 1. The majority of these survey questions have a median higher than 3, but \(qd18\) is the only one that has a 3 as its middle number.

# Create a list of plots
plots <- lapply(1:33, function(i) {
  # Store data in column.i as x
  x <- phone_133_all[,i]
  
  ggplot(data.frame(x), aes(x)) +
    geom_histogram( fill = "#964B00", color = "#964B00", bandwidth = 2) +
    geom_density(aes(y = 0.85*..count..), color = "black", adjust = 4, size = 1) +
    ggtitle(paste("Question", i)) +
    xlab("Scores") +
    ylab("Count") +
    xlim(0, 7) +
    theme_classic()
})

# Display the plots with 9 columns
gridExtra::grid.arrange(grobs = plots, ncol = 5)

The histograms help the reader better understand the distribution of the each survey question. There are several observations that help depict how customers responded:

  1. A majority of the questions have a greater count (200+) of responses from 3 to 5 (or 7).

  2. \(qd4\) and \(qd23\) have a slightly different distribution as there are more responses within the 1 and 2 range. This is because the range is 1 to 7 instead of all others that follow a 5-point scale.

  3. Typically, customers will choose 4 as their answer to a survey question.

Since there are assumptions of normality that need to be fulfilled later, it is critical to understand the skewness and kurtosis of each column. To be normal, a dataset needs to be symmetric and have a bell-shaped curve.

  1. Skewness range: -8.89 (\(qd12\)) to 9.40 (\(qd4\)). A negative skew means that the tail of the distribution is longer on the left side. Therefore, most of the data is concentrated on the right side of the histogram. The opposite can be said about positive skewness. Since there are no true zero values, this indicates that the distribution is not entirely symmetric around the mean. Based on prior class discussion though, the skewness can be considered as relatively small due to the context of the data.

  2. Kurtosis range: -7.821 (\(qd32\)) to 9.80 (\(qd12\)). The closer the value is to zero, the more flat the distribution relative to a normality. There are five questions where their values are within an absolute value of 1.2, which would insinuate that the distributions are relatively flat and possibly non-normal. Anything above zero would have a “leptokurtic” distribution, peaked higher than the expected normal distribution. If the value is negative, it follows a “platykurtic” distribution, indicating that it is flatter. This can occur when the data is more spread out and has a lower concentration around the mean.

2.1 Correlation Matrix

corr_phone_133 <- cor(phone_133_all)

A primary goal in factor analysis is to ensure that the variables are suitable to obtain distinct dimensions in order to reduce the number of items to explain and to interpret the results. The correlation matrix shows that some variables are highly correlated with one another while others have almost no relationship. Here are several examples:

One of the requirements needed for factor analysis is that some correlations in the matrix should exceed 30%. This criterion has been met. 2.2 Bartlett’s Test, KMO, & Anti-Image Correlation

bart_spher(phone_133_all)
##  Bartlett's Test of Sphericity
## 
## Call: bart_spher(x = phone_133_all)
## 
##      X2 = 30857.911
##      df = 528
## p-value < 2.22e-16

The Bartlett-Test (test of sphericity) ‘tests the hypothesis that the sample originates from a population, where are variables are uncorrelated’. The main assumption is that the variables in a population are normally distributed. Since this is not the case for five predictors, this test may be invalid. Instead, other tests like the Kaiser-Meyer-Olkin (KMO) or Measure of Sampling Adequacy (MSA) can be utilized and are more appropriate.

KMOTEST <- KMOS(phone_133_all)

The KMO test measures sampling adequacy (MSA) by taking the ‘ratio of the sum of squared correlations to the sum of squared correlations plus the sum of squared partial correlations’. If the value is greater than 0.6, the data can be reduced to less dimensions. For this factor analysis, it surpasses that requirement at 0.96, which means that the data is a good fit for FA since it has a value close to 1.

kmo_results <- KMO(phone_133_all)

  ggtitle("Diagonal Elements of KMO's Matrix") +
  theme_minimal()

The Anti-Image Correlation ‘measures the sampling adequacy for each individual variable’. From using this type of matrix, ‘items that do not correlate with any of the factors can be easily identified. If a value is below 0.5, the corresponding variable should be removed from the analysis’. As seen above, all elements are above that threshold. But, \(qd4\) stands apart because it is much lower at 0.64 and the next lowest value (\(qd23\)) is at 0.90. \(qd4\) will be on the watch list as the analysis continues.

Additionally, it is interesting to look at the MSA diagonals because it relates to how well those factors/dimensions have been covered throughout the survey questions. In the instance of \(qd4\) and \(qd23\), they both are quite high compared to every other question according to the blue dots. Therefore, we add \(qd23\) to the watch list.

2.3 Principal Axis Factoring

Principal axis factoring (PAF) is an exploratory factor method that is used to help represent a multitude of relationships among normally distributed or scale variables in a parsimonious manner. First, we explore PAF because we want to review the correlation matrix in a modified way. This means that the correlations of each item with itself are replaced with a “communality”— a measure of that item’s relation to all other items. This means that this type of analysis is directed at understanding only the covariation among the variables.

To obtain the best model, we will test several scenarios with different factors to see which ones have the lowest \(BIC\) and \(rms\), but the highest \(fit\). Earlier in the correlation matrix, there were ten groupings of questions and five of those will be tested to get the best results to find the final solution.

Note: Anything lower than 5-factor or more than 10-factor will not be shown due to poor results.

FA6 <- fa(phone_133_all, nfactors = 6, rotate = "varimax", fm = "pa") # Principal factor solution (pa)

Next, we will run the different combinations of factors, and removed ‘watch list’ variables to analyze how the loadings compare to the relative factors.

The loadings are an important estimation when it comes to analyzing the correlation between each observed variable and the proposed factors. They can be thought of as weights. When the weight is higher, that indicates the question is associated with the factor. Therefore, we should only possibly consider two of the models, FA8_423 and FA9_all. The other two have issues with the loading weights are too low or no questions in a certain factor. even though we could argue that the Exclusion 8-factors Loadings - PAF is the better choice due to model measurements, we will continue to go through each analysis with both for further comparison to ensure the best model is chosen.

# Create a data frame of eigenvalues and factor numbers
eigenvalues <- data.frame(factor_number = 1:length(FA8_423$values), eigenvalue = FA8_423$values)

# Create a logical vector indicating which eigenvalues are greater than 1
greater_than_1 <- FA8_423$values > 1

# Create the plot using ggplot()
ggplot(eigenvalues, aes(x = 1:length(FA8_423$values), y = FA8_423$values)) +
  geom_point(size = 3, color = "#964B00") +
  geom_abline(intercept = 1, slope = 0, color = "blue") +
  geom_point(data = eigenvalues[greater_than_1, ], aes(x = factor_number, y = eigenvalue), size = 3, color = "#D2B48C") +
  labs(x = "Factor Number", y = "Eigenvalue", title = "PAF Scree plot") +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = rel(1.5), face = "bold"),
        axis.title = element_text(size = rel(1.2)),
        axis.text = element_text(size = rel(1.2)),
        axis.line = element_line(size = 0.5),
        panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
        panel.border = element_blank()) +
  annotate("text", x = 25, y = 13, label = "Eigenvalues < 1", colour="#964B00") + annotate("text", x = 25, y = 14, label = "Eigenvalues >= 1", colour="#D2B48C") + theme(plot.title = element_text(face="bold"))
## Warning: The `size` argument of `element_line()` is deprecated as of ggplot2 3.4.0.
## ℹ Please use the `linewidth` argument instead.

The graph above shows a screeplot, which is a ‘graphical representation of eigenvalues by ordering them according to their size’. The rule is subjective because the analyst is supposed to retain the eigenvalues above the break or elbow of the curve. This is very difficult to visualize. If we had to guess, it would most likely be 4-factors or 8-factors. Therefore, a more concrete approach is to look at the Kaiser criterion. The main rule to follow is that only eigenvalues greater than 1 should be extracted. If that eigenvalue is less than 1, this means that the factor ‘contributes less than a single variable in explaining total variance’. It is seen within the screeplot that there is an 5-factor solution by the two-toned points indicating which eigenvalues are above that threshold.

2.4 Final Factor Solution

To obtain the final model, there were various steps that needed to occur in order to figure out how many factors and which questions were to be kept moving forward. There were several prominent findings that aided our decision.

  1. From the beginning, \(qd4\) and \(qd23\) had a weak relationship with the other survey questions. Specific to these questions, they stood out because they referred to prestige and distinctiveness, but there were no additional predictors that fell within those categories. Additionally, how they were treated in the correlation matrix as separate entities showed that they should not be grouped together under one factor and the analyses to follow showed that.

  2. Once acknowledging the watch list, the PAF helped conclude the number of factors that would produce the best model. There is a trade-off between better fit due to added complexity and losing some fit to obtain a more parsimonious model which is the end goal for PAF. Therefore, the 8-factor solution seemed to perform better with the lowest \(BIC\). The reader show be cautious about this decision as there are multiple ways to choose how many factors should be represented in the model. 

  3. The unique values for questions 4 and 23 were extremely high compared to all others. This was a red flag.

  4. The choice to remove questions 4 and 23 and to use only 8-factors was solidified by reviewing the communalities. Those questions clearly did not belong as the third lowest value was 0.40 above \(qd23\)’s value.

fa.diagram(FA8_423)

Overall, the best fit model was FA8_423 due to these reasons. Additionally, they show clear loadings for the eight dimensions. A presentation of the loadings are in the diagram above. The eight factors can then be described through various dimensions outlined in the PDF provided in class. Before revealing those eight groups, it should be noted that we have agreed that ‘Conformance’ does not fit with the three questions that fall under PA6. Therefore, we recommend that the dimension and description changes to a factor that relates to ‘material.’

Below highlights the eight dimensions that could be matched to the 8-factor solution.

2.4.1 Serviceability

Involves the consumer’s ease of obtaining repair service (access to service centers and/or ease of self service), the responsiveness of service personnel and the reliability of the performed service
- Resource: Brucks, Zeithaml, Naylor (2000)

The speed, courtesy, competence and ease of repair – the elapsed time before service is restored, the timelines
- Resource: Garvin David A. (1988), Managing Quality, The free press, New York

2.4.2 Performance

How well the product does what it is supposed to do – might well be multidimensional itself – e.g for cars power, comfort, safety – must perform well and must do so consistently. This consistency can be referred reliability or dependability
- Resource: Brucks, Zeithaml, Naylor (2000)

Primary operating characteristics of a product e.g. for an automobile acceleration, handling, cruising speed and comfort
- Resource: Garvin David A. (1988), Managing Quality, The free press, New York

2.4.3 Material (New Dimension)

2.4.4 Durability

Involves the length of time the product lasts, the length of time the product works properly (i.e whether the product needs frequent servicing), how well the product holds up under adverse conditions such as weather heavy use or misuse
- Resource: Brucks, Zeithaml, Naylor (2000)

A measure of product life – the amount of use one gets from a product before it breaks down and replacement is regarded as preferable to continued repair (has technical and economic dimensions)
- Resource: Garvin David A. (1988), Managing Quality, The free press, New York

2.4.5 Aesthetics/Appearance

How a product looks, feels, sounds, tastes or smells – clearly a matter of personal judgments and a reflection of individual preferences – very subjective
- Resource: Garvin David A. (1988), Managing Quality, The free press, New York

2.4.6 Ease of Use

Involves the consumer’s ability to start and operate the product as well as clarity of instrumentation and instructions – focus groups considered ease of use as an important dimension of quality
- Resource: Brucks, Zeithaml, Naylor (2000)

2.4.7 Features/Versatility

The number and complexity of the characteristics that distinguish the model or brand from a stripped-down model. The bells and whistles generally enable the product to perform more functions
- Resource: Brucks, Zeithaml, Naylor (2000)

The bells and whistles of a products, those secondary characteristics that supplement the basic functioning of the product
- Resource: Garvin David A. (1988), Managing Quality, The free press, New York

2.4.8 Reliability/Flawlessness

Reflects the probability of a product’s malfunctioning or failing within a specified period of time – can be measured with mean time to first failure (MTBF)
- Resource: Garvin David A. (1988), Managing Quality, The free press, New York

2.5 Principal Component Analysis (PCA)

The second factor extraction method is PCA. The goal here is to produce an empirical summary of a data set by reducing the dimensionality to capture relationships between variables and analyze patterns. Since the exercise states to run a PCA on the final solution from the PAF results, we will include eight factors and not include questions 4 and 23, as well as explore other options.

plot_PCA <- psych::principal(phone_133_all, rotate = "varimax", nfactors = 33, scores = TRUE)

# Create a data frame of eigenvalues and factor numbers

  theme_bw() +

Since there are many criterion to decide on the number of factor extraction, we start by looking at the eigenvalues. In PAF, there were only 5-factors above 1, and now there appear to be 8-factors when we start from stratch. This is not the only measure to review though. Once again, we will explore \(rms\), and \(fit\) to find the optimal model.

Since we have 8-factors listed above, we will look at factors 6 through 10, with and without questions 4 and 23.

  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = rel(1.5), face = "bold"),
        axis.title = element_text(size = rel(1.2)),
        axis.text = element_text(size = rel(1.2)),
        axis.line = element_line(size = 0.5),
        panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
        panel.border = element_blank()) +
  annotate("text", x = 30, y = 13, label = "Eigenvalues < 1", colour="#964B00") + annotate("text", x = 30, y = 14, label = "Eigenvalues >= 1", colour="#D2B48C") + theme(plot.title = element_text(face="bold"))

After running both scree plots for those two models, PCA8_423 shows a 7-factor solution while PCA10_all shows eight dimensions. To check the total variance explained for both, we run the eigenvalues and respective variance distributed to each factor.

It is clear that there are distinct loadings shown within the rotated matrices. In addition, both explain over 80% of the total variance. What is seen now though is that RC10 and RC7 are broken out by themselves. These correlate to questions 4 and 23. This is troubling because even though there is a distinctiveness/prestige dimension, there would need to be additional questions in order to include these if that was a possibility. Therefore, the final model once again with be 8-factors, excluding those variables.

Based on the final solution for PAF and what was obtained through PCA, the results ended up being the same at the end but not concretely throughout the analysis. For example, PAF wanted to group those two questions into one factor while PCA wanted them to be independent of each other due to their low correlations to any other predictors. Since we knew that we had two watch list values, we built additional models to ensure that we captured everything so nothing fell through the cracks. 

Throughout this analysis, the main objective has been to understand the importance of perceived quality in building a competitive advantage in the smartphone industry. Several studies support the claim that changes in quality perceptions have been positively correlated with the firm’s profitability and successful corporate performance. However, there is not a standard product quality scale that exists today. To combat this problem, a major smartphone producer kick started a project to measure product quality of smartphones in terms of its constituent dimensions. More importantly though, product management’s goal is to obtain a deeper understanding about which quality dimensions significantly impact key outcome variables such as willingness to pay premium and repurchase intentions.

Out of the nine quality dimensions defined, we found that eight factors explained the relevance of a customer’s repurchase behavior. These are mentioned above with their respective definitions. This is important because the eigenvalues show the contribution of a specific factor in measuring the total variance. With this 8-factor solution, it contributed 84.1% of the total variation. Having a high eigenvalue means that more weight should be given in a subsequent analysis, like Problem 2 and that those factors will possibly provide more information than the others when it comes to wanting to focus on the most important dimensions.

3.1 Oblique Factor Analysis

Compute factor scores for your factors and name and label them appropriately. Run a regression analysis with the factor scores of the quality dimensions as independent and both the mean score of willingness to pay premium and repurchase intention as dependent variables

Run an oblique factor analysis with the variables of your final solution in Exercise 1 using Promax.

Based on the Promax factor analysis conducted, the loadings are shown for eight rotated components, with each variable assigned to the component where it has the highest loading. The loadings table shows the relationship between the different survey questions and each factor. It appears that all items have loadings above 0.60.

In terms of the factors themselves, Factor 2 has the highest proportion of variance explained (13.5%), and is most correlated with \(qd24\) and \(qd14\), before getting to more moderate correlations. Factor 1 explains 12% of the variance, highly correlated with \(qd7\) and \(qd2\). When accounting for all eight factors, it explains 76.2% of total variation. Out of all the 33 questions though, the highest correlation is from MR7, question 25, at 97.6%.

Overall, these findings indicate that the quality dimensions can be classified into eight factors that are correlated with one another and account for a significant amount of variance in the data. These variables (factors) can be used to gain a better understanding of the relationship between quality perceptions and key outcome variables like willingness to pay a premium (WTP) and repurchase intentions (RI).

The communality corresponds to the percentage of variance in a variable explained by factors because the questions are standardized to account for the possibility of different scales. If the communality of any of the questions is less than 0.5, we would consider removing those values because they would not accurately represent the factors in the model. The variables with a high communality are likely to be important for understanding the underlying dimensions of the data and should be included in further analysis. The lowest communality is 0.63, so there are no variables on the watch list because the gaps are below the threshold.

There is, for example, a strong positive correlation between Performance and Features, Aesthetics and Performance, and Ease of Use and Performance. This implies that these variables are positively related; as one increases, so does the other. There are also a few weak negative correlations. For example, there is a weak negative correlation between Reliability and Willingness to Pay, as well as a weak negative correlation between Material and Willingness to Pay. This indicates that as the latter factors rise, the former tend to fall.

pred_corr_matrix <- cor(pred_df)
corrplot(as.matrix(pred_corr_matrix, numbers), tl.col = "black", number.cex = 0.8, method = 'color')

3.2 Regressions of WTP and RI

The first two regression analyses use different models to predict Willingness to Pay (WTP). The first model has eight factors and two additional variables, \(qd23\) and \(qd4\). The second model only employs eight factors.

In both models, the variables Serviceability, Performance, Ease_of_Use, and Features have positive coefficients and are statistically significant. This indicates that, regardless of the model used, these variables have a positive effect on WTP.

Material has a positive coefficient in the first model, as does Aesthetics, which has a marginally significant positive coefficient (p-value = 0.109). Material has a positive coefficient in the second model, but Aesthetics has a positive coefficient that is not statistically significant (p-value = 0.058). These differences imply that the addition of two additional variables, \(qd23\) and \(qd4\), may have influenced the relationship between Aesthetics and WTP.

The adjusted R-squared values for both models are relatively low, indicating that there may be other factors influencing WTP that are not captured by the model.

The third regression analysis predicts Repurchase Intention (RI) using the same eight variables as well as two additional variables, \(qd23\) and \(qd4\). Serviceability, Performance, and Ease_of_Use have positive coefficients and are statistically significant, indicating that they have a positive effect on RI. Although the material has a positive coefficient, it is only marginally significant (p-value = 0.055).

The adjusted R-squared value for the RI model is also relatively low, implying that there may be other factors influencing RI that the model does not account for.

Overall, the model with 8 factors and no additional variables appears to be a good fit for both WTP and RI based on the coefficients and statistical significance.

#run regression WTP with 8 factors, qd23, and qd4
wtp_model <- lm(Willingness_to_Pay ~ Serviceability + Performance + Aesthetics + Ease_of_Use + Features + Material + Reliability + Durability + qd4 + qd23, data = factor_scores_all)

summary(wtp_model, standardise = TRUE)

3.3 Mean Scores

Compute mean scores for the three willingness to pay premium items (\(wtp1\)-\(wtp3\)) and the two repurchase intention items (\(ri1\)-\(ri2\)).

Run a regression analysis with the factor scores of the quality dimensions as independent and both the mean score of willingness to pay premium and repurchase intention as dependent variables.

The regression analysis suggests that the quality dimensions have a significant impact on both willingness to pay premium and repurchase intention for phones. Among the quality dimensions, Ease_of_Use and Features have the most significant effect on willingness to pay premium and Ease_of_Use and Performance to repurchase intention. The other quality dimensions, such as Aesthetics, Material, Reliability, and Durability, also have some impact, but their effect is relatively weaker.

From an industrial perspective, these findings imply that phone manufacturers should focus on enhancing Ease_of_Use and Performance to increase both willingness to pay premium and repurchase intention among customers. Additionally, phone manufacturers could also consider improving other quality dimensions, such as Aesthetics, Features, Material, Reliability, and Durability, to further enhance customer satisfaction and loyalty. However, since the effect of these dimensions is relatively weaker, manufacturers should prioritize their efforts on Ease_of_Use and Performance. Overall, these findings could provide valuable insights for phone manufacturers to develop high-quality products that meet the needs and expectations of their customers.

# Calculate row-wise mean scores for wtp and ri
phone_all$mean_wtp <- rowMeans(phone_all[, c("wtp1", "wtp2", "wtp3")], na.rm = TRUE)
phone_all$mean_ri <- rowMeans(phone_all[, c("ri1", "ri2")], na.rm = TRUE)

phone_all <- phone_all[,-c(4,23)]

3.4 Brand Analysis

Do the results of the regression analysis for repurchase intentions differ across brands e.g. Samsung versus Apple versus LG. What do the results of these regressions imply? Please compare the brands on the factor scores. What are points of parity and points of difference for the different brands.

In the outputs below we can see that the coefficients for each independent variable vary across brands.

The regression output for Apple shows that Serviceability, Aesthetics, and Ease_of_Use have significant positive coefficients at the 0.05 level, implying that these factors have a positive impact on customers’ willingness to pay for Apple phones. Performance, Features, Material, Reliability, and Durability, on the other hand, do not have significant coefficients at the 0.05 level, implying that these factors do not have a statistically significant impact on willingness to pay for Apple phones among customers who highly rated the brand.

Serviceability, Performance, Aesthetics, Ease_of_Use, Features, Material, and Durability coefficients are all positive in Samsung data, but not all of them are statistically significant. At the 5% significance level, only Ease_of_Use and Material are statistically significant. Serviceability, Aesthetics, and Reliability all have negative coefficients, but only Reliability is statistically significant at the 5% significance level. This implies that for brandrec2 data, these characteristics are not significant predictors of WTP.

Serviceability, Aesthetics, Ease_of_Use, Features, Material, and Durability do not appear to have a statistically significant relationship with mean_wtp in LG data, as their p-values are greater than the 0.05 significance level. When attempting to predict or explain variation in mean_wtp among respondents in brandrec3_df, it appears that reliability may be the most important factor to consider.

3.5 Factor Score Comparison

Please compare the brands on the factor scores. What are points of parity and points of difference for the different brands.

According to the table, Apple(1) and Samsung(2) have relatively similar factor scores in Reliability (both positive), whereas LG has relatively lower factor scores across all attributes.

It is difficult to determine the point of parity from the table below. We can see that there are significant differences between brands in terms of points across the factor scores.

brand_scores <- combined_df_brands |> 
  group_by(brandrec) |> 
  summarise(across(everything(), mean))
brand_scores <- brand_scores[-c(2:39)]
brand_scores
